    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper by Deffayet and Woodard proposes a modified gravity theory \u2014 requiring no new particles \u2014 that the authors argue can simultaneously account for why galaxies rotate the way they do (usually attributed to dark matter) and reproduce the large-scale cosmological imprints of dark matter. The review board found the individual building blocks credible, since each was established in prior published work by the same group, but unanimously agreed that the paper's central new claim \u2014 that the two regimes are connected by a single smooth mathematical equation \u2014 has not been demonstrated even in a simplified toy calculation. The most important caveat is that a key quantity in the model appears to approach zero near the present cosmic epoch, which could undermine the very cosmological equivalence the model claims to provide.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper synthesizes a prior nonlocal mimetic-gravity CDM construction (Deffayet & Woodard 2024, ref [15]) and a prior nonlocal MOND realization (Deffayet, Esposito-Farese & Woodard 2011/2014, refs [11,12]) into a single Lagrangian via a proposed interpolating equation (eq. 33), governed by a function f(X) where X is a nonlocal Ricci-tensor invariant. Each limiting regime is sound by prior construction: the cosmological sector is definitionally equivalent to a conserved pressureless dark matter stress tensor at linear order, and the gravitationally bound sector reproduces the BTFR and lensing condition \u03a6=\u03a8 in the static spherically symmetric limit. Three reviewers converge on two major unresolved issues across both review cycles: (1) the interpolation mechanism is entirely qualitative \u2014 eq. (33) has correct asymptotic design but no quantitative demonstration, toy geometry solution, or branch-selection analysis in a realistic transition spacetime exists; and (2) the cosmological invariant X\u21920 at late times (z\u22480, Appendix 7), potentially reactivating the MOND correction during current cosmic epochs and undermining the CDM mimicry the model relies upon. Stability of the synthesized interpolating model, nonlinear structure formation in the transition regime, and cluster-scale phenomenology are all deferred to future work."
